equation_narrative.headline: Model misreads C-terminal glycine as cysteine despite strong evolutionary signal
equation_narrative.story: Position 76 is the penultimate residue in ubiquitin's C-terminal tail (sequence context LRLRG[G]). Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with small, flexible residues, reading minimal structural contacts (only 1 neighbor) but receiving moderate co-evolutionary signal from 3 coupled positions. The logit lens shows early preference for polar/small residues (S, A) that gradually shifts toward glycine by layer 20, reaching 62% at layer 23. However, in the decision phase (L24-33), cysteine-specific prediction channels activate explosively—rising from 1.8% at L23 to 81% at L33—while glycine collapses from its 94% peak at L26 to just 13% at L33. The model's final choice reflects a misinterpretation of the C-terminal context as favoring cysteine's small size and potential for post-translational modification over glycine's unique conformational flexibility.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather sparse structural information but significant evolutionary context. With only 1 structural contact, the model relies heavily on sequence patterns and co-evolutionary coupling to 3 positions. Early attention features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508 with 44+ projections) encode local sequence identity. By layer 9, the representation shifts toward charged/polar character as the model reads the surrounding arginine-rich context (LRLRG). Mid-layer features (F18:595, F18:6841) encode C-terminal position awareness. The logit lens trajectory reflects this evolution: starting with polar residues (S at 23%, A at 20% at L0), transitioning through charged candidates (K, R dominate L6-13), then converging on small residues (G reaches 62% by L23). This is not prediction but context assembly—the representation encodes 'C-terminal, small, flexible' character.
perception_phase.context_character: C-terminal position in a flexible tail region with minimal structural burial (1 contact), surrounded by charged residues (LRLR motif). The representation by L23 is consistent with small, conformationally flexible residues suitable for terminal positions.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: only 1 residue within contact distance—minimal burial constraint
Co-evolutionary signal: 3 coupled positions provide moderate evolutionary constraint
C-terminal encoding: F18:595 (9.32 proj) and F18:6841 (9.02 proj) activate, indicating terminal position awareness
Local sequence reading: attention heads at L17 (velocity +1.65) and L22 (velocity +1.77) integrate LRLRG motif context

decision_phase.summary: The transition to decision occurs sharply at L24-27. Cysteine-specific prediction channels emerge: F24:6593 (23.72 proj) activates at L24, followed by massive MLP support at L26-27 (N26:501 with 0.63 G-proj, N26:1294 with 0.51 G-proj initially favor glycine, but are overwhelmed by cysteine votes). The critical collapse happens at L32-33: MLP neurons N32:4924 (-1.12 G-proj, voting for E/Q) and N32:4433 (-0.99 G-proj, voting for I/V) actively suppress glycine, while F33:132 (92.36 proj), F33:3601 (83.2 proj), and F33:9180 (78.81 proj) drive cysteine to 81%. Glycine peaks at 94% at L26 but loses decisively in the final layers.
decision_phase.transition: Layer 23 marks the perception-to-decision boundary: the representation is 62% glycine-consistent, reflecting assembled context. At L24, F24:6593 (23.72 proj) activates—the first high-specificity cysteine prediction channel. By L25-26, the model commits: MLP neurons begin casting amino-acid-specific votes rather than encoding context features.

candidates.narrative: Cysteine emerges explosively in the decision phase despite minimal early presence (1.8% at L23). At L24, F24:6593 (23.72 proj) activates as the first cysteine-specific channel. The decisive surge occurs at L32-33: F33:132 (92.36 proj), F33:3601 (83.2 proj), and F33:9180 (78.81 proj) fire strongly, while MLP neurons at L32 provide net support. Cysteine rises from 2.1% at L29 to 81% at L33, winning through late-stage prediction channels that interpret the C-terminal context as favoring cysteine's small size and reactive thiol group over glycine's unique flexibility.
key_evidence: F33:132 (MLP, 92.36 proj) — strongest cysteine-specific feature in final layer
F33:3601 (MLP, 83.2 proj) and F33:9180 (MLP, 78.81 proj) — additional cysteine prediction channels
F24:6593 (MLP, 23.72 proj) — early cysteine channel activation at decision boundary

candidates.narrative: Glycine is the true residue and dominates the perception phase, reaching 62% at L23 and peaking at 94% at L26 as the model correctly assembles C-terminal context. Strong support comes from MLP neurons N21:3914 (1.03 G-proj) and attention heads reading co-evolutionary signal (L32 head 16: 2.16 proj, head 15: 1.90 proj). However, glycine collapses in L32-33 as suppressive neurons activate: N32:4924 (-1.12 G-proj, voting E/Q) and N31:4325 (-1.10 G-proj, voting D/Y) actively erase glycine probability. The model misinterprets the assembled context in the final decision layers.
key_evidence: N21:3914 (1.03 G-proj) — strongest glycine-writing neuron, peaks at L21
L32 head 16 (2.16 proj) and head 15 (1.90 proj) — co-evolutionary readers supporting glycine
N32:4924 (-1.12 G-proj) and N31:4325 (-1.10 G-proj) — decisive glycine suppressors in final layers

candidates.narrative: Alanine leads the logit lens at L0 (20%) and remains prominent through L12-15 (peaks at 18% L12). This reflects the representation's early character: small, hydrophobic-leaning residues are consistent with minimal structural contacts and C-terminal position. Alanine is not a model prediction at these layers—it's an artifact of the representation encoding 'small, simple' chemistry. Alanine fades as the model refines toward glycine's unique flexibility requirements, dropping to 3.6% by L33.
key_evidence: 20% at L0 — logit lens artifact reflecting small-residue representation character
Sustained through L12-15 as model encodes minimal burial context

candidates.narrative: Serine leads at L0 (23%) and remains competitive through L17 (17.5%), reflecting the representation's early polar character as the model reads the charged local context (LRLR motif). The logit lens projects toward polar residues because the accumulated features encode surface-exposed, charged-neighbor chemistry. This is not a serine prediction—it's the representation's chemical signature. Serine fades as C-terminal and flexibility features accumulate, dropping to 1.1% by L33.
key_evidence: 23% at L0 and 17.5% at L17 — representation consistent with polar, surface-exposed context
Declines as C-terminal position encoding overrides general polarity signal

turning_points.description: The representation converges on glycine-consistent character as C-terminal context fully assembles. Glycine rises from 13.8% at L20 to 61.8% at L23 through combined attention and MLP activity (L22: +1.77 attn, +1.89 MLP toward G). Key neurons N21:3914 (1.03 G-proj), N22:3890 (0.30 G-proj), and N23:2724 (0.42 G-proj) write glycine-compatible features. This is the model correctly encoding 'C-terminal, flexible, small' requirements—but it's still perception, not decision.

The decision phase begins: cysteine-specific prediction channels activate while glycine maintains dominance. F24:6593 (23.72 proj) fires at L24, marking the first high-specificity cysteine feature. At L26-27, competing MLP neurons cast votes: N26:501 (0.63 G-proj) and N26:1294 (0.51 G-proj) support glycine, but N27:3781 (-0.76 G-proj) and N27:3906 (-0.43 G-proj) begin suppressing it. Glycine peaks at 94% at L26 but the cysteine machinery is now active.

The decisive reversal: cysteine prediction channels fire maximally while glycine suppressors activate. F33:132 (92.36 proj), F33:3601 (83.2 proj), and F33:9180 (78.81 proj) drive cysteine from 2% to 81%. Simultaneously, N32:4924 (-1.12 G-proj, voting E/Q/Y) and N32:4433 (-0.99 G-proj, voting I/V/W) actively erase glycine probability. Attention heads L32:5 (-2.30 proj) and L32:16 (+2.16 proj) create conflicting signals. The MLP stream dominates: L32 MLP contributes -6.0 to glycine, L33 MLP contributes -6.6, overwhelming the correct evolutionary signal.

deep_dives.label: Early context encoding (L1, L9)
deep_dives.caption: Layer 1 features encode local sequence identity and position. Layer 9 features show the representation transitioning toward charged/polar character as the model reads the LRLR motif context. These are not predictions—they're the model building a representation of 'what's here.'

deep_dives.label: C-terminal awareness (L18)
deep_dives.caption: Layer 18 features encode abstract positional properties. F18:595 (9.32 proj) and F18:6841 (9.02 proj) indicate the model has recognized this as a C-terminal position, shifting the representation toward terminal-appropriate residue types.

deep_dives.label: Perception-phase MLP (L16-23)
deep_dives.caption: MLP neurons in L16-23 write glycine-compatible features as the model assembles C-terminal context. N21:3914 (1.03 G-proj) is the strongest glycine writer, encoding flexibility requirements. These neurons are building a representation, not yet casting prediction votes.

deep_dives.label: Cysteine prediction channels (L24, L33)
deep_dives.caption: Layer 24 marks the decision boundary: F24:6593 (23.72 proj) is the first high-specificity cysteine channel. Layer 33 features are pure prediction: F33:132 (92.36 proj), F33:3601 (83.2 proj), F33:9180 (78.81 proj) drive the final cysteine decision.

deep_dives.label: Final decision neurons (L31-32)
deep_dives.caption: L31-32 MLP neurons cast the decisive votes. Glycine suppressors N32:4924 (-1.12 G-proj, voting E/Q) and N31:4325 (-1.10 G-proj, voting D/Y) actively erase glycine probability. Meanwhile, cysteine gains indirect support as these neurons vote for other small residues, creating space for cysteine channels to dominate.

deep_dives.label: Co-evolutionary attention (L31-32)
deep_dives.caption: L32 head 16 (2.16 proj, 54% coevol attention) and head 15 (1.90 proj, 69% coevol attention) read evolutionary coupling signal supporting glycine. L31 head 13 (1.97 proj, 100% coevol attention) also supports the correct answer. However, these signals are overwhelmed by the MLP stream's cysteine votes in the final layers.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly assembles C-terminal context through L1-26, recognizing position 76 as penultimate in ubiquitin's flexible tail with minimal structural constraints. Glycine dominates the representation (94% at L26) as the model encodes the need for conformational flexibility. However, in the final decision layers (L32-33), cysteine-specific prediction channels (F33:132, F33:3601, F33:9180) activate explosively while MLP neurons (N32:4924, N31:4325) suppress glycine. The model appears to misinterpret the C-terminal context as favoring cysteine's small size and reactive chemistry over glycine's unique backbone flexibility. The error occurs despite strong co-evolutionary signal from attention heads (L32:16, L32:15) that correctly support glycine—the MLP stream's cysteine votes in L32-33 (contributing -12.6 total to glycine logit) decisively override the evolutionary evidence.
